<subSubSection id="CB971AE1FFBBFFB5FF21B4D3C11F214C" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8332496AFFBBFFB5FF21B4D3C88924E5" blockId="3.[185,1151,413,3274]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Remarks. All specimens were taken in the forest, far from water, flying close to the ground or sitting on sticks or stemlets of low growing plants. The larval habitat is unknown. but might not be lotic.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8332496AFFBBFFB5FF21B7C6C11F214C" blockId="3.[185,1151,413,3274]" lastBlockId="3.[1271,2235,414,3269]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FF21B7C6CBAF2524" authority="Selys" authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[230,640,1757,1794]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto" status="sensu stricto">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FF21B7C6CB222524" box="[230,525,1757,1794]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
Selys
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="AACA2803FFBBFFB5FD52B7C6CABD2524" box="[661,914,1757,1794]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" sensu="stricto">sensu stricto</taxonomicNameLabel>
is monoty pic. Those species included in 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FCB5B609C866254A" authority="Forster" authorityName="Forster" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FCB5B609CD522511" box="[882,1149,1810,1847]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Allopodagrion</emphasis>
Forster
</taxonomicName>
, currentlv considered a subgenus of the former, differ in many important features from 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FF07B6AAC8FF25F0" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[192,464,1969,2006]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalopus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FF07B6AAC9C525F0" box="[192,234,1969,2006]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FEC0B6AAC8FF25F0" box="[263,464,1969,2006]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">megalopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FE17B6AAC8FA25F0" box="[464,469,1969,2006]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">.</emphasis>
Therefore I think that full generic rank for 
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FEB1B6FDCBA42A2D" box="[374,651,2022,2059]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FEB1B6FDCBAA2A2D" box="[374,645,2022,2059]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Allopodagrion</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
as originally assigned to by 
<bibRefCitation id="E71C349BFFBBFFB5FEC3B908CB242A67" author="FORSTER, F." box="[260,523,2067,2113]" journalOrPublisher="Wiener Entomologische Zeitung" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" pagination="51 - 56" part="29" refId="ref10370" refString="FORSTER, F. 1910 - Beitrage zu den Gattungen und Arten der Libellen II. Wiener Entomologische Zeitung, 29: 51 - 56." title="Beitrage zu den Gattungen und Arten der Libellen II" type="journal article" year="1910">Forster (1910)</bibRefCitation>
, is clearly justified. The strongest argument for doing so is given by penis morphology: The penis of 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FD09B99FCADB2A8F" authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[718,1012,2180,2217]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FD09B99FCADB2A8F" box="[718,1012,2180,2217]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is lestine (Fig. 11-12), while that of 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FCF1B9A2CD6D2AF8" box="[822,1090,2233,2270]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FCF1B9A2CD6D2AF8" box="[822,1090,2233,2270]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Allopodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is typically megapodagrionine (
<figureCitation id="1BB655EFFFBBFFB5FCC8B9F5CADA2B35" box="[783,1013,2286,2323]" captionStart="Plate II" captionStartId="14.[193,288,3057,3091]" captionTargetBox="[212,2070,564,2898]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Plate II: Figure 7. Chalcopteryx scintillans, female ultimate instar exuviae, labium, ventral view. Figures 8-10. Dimeragrion unturanense sp.n. (8) holotype male, abdominal segment 10 with anal appendages, left lateral view; (9) same, dorsal view; (10) female, paratype, tip of abdomen, left lateral view. Figure3 11-12. Megapodagrion megalopus, male. (11) penis, ri.ght lateral view; (12) same, ventral view. Figures 13-14. Allopodagrion oscillans (Venezuela, Tachira, Betania). male. (13) penis, right lateral view; (14) same, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3266069/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Figs. 13-14</figureCitation>
) with two conspicuos cornua as have, for example, 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FB84B838CAB92B5B" authority="Calvert, Heteragrion Selys" authorityName="Calvert, Heteragrion Selys" authorityYear="1913" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Dimeragrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FF06B843C8AE2B5B" box="[193,385,2392,2429]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Dimeragrion</emphasis>
Calvert, Heteragrion Selys
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FC72B843CBDB2B94" authority="Williamson, Philogenia Selys" authorityName="Williamson, Philogenia Selys" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Oxystigma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
Oxystigma Williamson, 
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FE7FB896CB542B94" box="[440,635,2445,2482]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Philogenia</emphasis>
Selys
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FCA9B896CB2B2BCE" authority="Racenis. Petiolation" authorityName="Racenis. Petiolation" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Sciotropis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FCA9B896CD0C2B94" box="[878,1059,2445,2482]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Sciotropis</emphasis>
Racenis. Petiolation
</taxonomicName>
of wings ceases far distad from cux in 
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FE8EB8ECCB57283A" box="[329,632,2551,2588]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FE8EB8ECCB5E283A" authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[329,625,2551,2588]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megapodagrion</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but very close to, or even proximally of cux in 
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FDBFBB37C80D28A3" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FDBFBB37CAA92877" box="[632,902,2604,2641]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Allopodagrion</taxonomicName>
. Megapodgrion
</emphasis>
has two supplementary sectors between IR2 and R3 and two more between R3 and IR3 whiIe 
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FF32BBD1CB2C28C9" box="[245,515,2762,2799]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Ailopodagrion</emphasis>
has only one in each space. The fore wings are shorter than the hind wings in 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FBF3BBE4C885297F" authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FBF3BBE4C885297F" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but equal or longer in 
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FCADBA2FCD54297F" box="[874,1147,2868,2905]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FCADBA2FCD59297F" box="[874,1142,2868,2905]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Allopodagrion</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Adult 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FE87BA72CB4829A8" authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[320,615,2921,2958]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FE87BA72CB4829A8" box="[320,615,2921,2958]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are mottled with brown, the two apical abdominal segments are in thtl male densely covered with white pruinescence Adult 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FE85BD1CCB602E0A" box="[322,591,3079,3116]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FE85BD1CCB602E0A" box="[322,591,3079,3116]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Allopodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are black with blue patches on the mesepisterna, which might be covered by blue pruinescence, tip of abdomen has no pruinescence. The larval habitat of 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FCDDBDBECD6F2EEC" authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[794,1088,3237,3274]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FCDDBDBECD6F2EEC" box="[794,1088,3237,3274]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unknown, but adults are found in lowland rain forest away from running water flying close to the ground. All species of 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5F97FB313CEEA200B" box="[1720,1989,520,557]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5F97FB313CEEA200B" box="[1720,1989,520,557]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Allopodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are instead breeding in small mountain creeks in partly open or closed forest and do not abandon the water courses. It seems, therefore, that besides of the long legs, 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FA79B3C7CFE32127" box="[1470,1740,732,769]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FA79B3C7CFE32127" box="[1470,1740,732,769]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Allopodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not share more characters with 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5FA2AB20BCE3C2113" authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[1517,1811,784,821]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B1F99578FFBBFFB5FA2AB20BCE3C2113" box="[1517,1811,784,821]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than with 
<taxonomicName id="448D32E9FFBBFFB5F835B20BC19C2113" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[2034,2227,784,821]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Philogenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Philogenia</taxonomicName>
or with any other of the compared genera
</paragraph>
